<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1921-09-09T11:45:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1921-08-31T23:00:00-05:00" n="616" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d616">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">500. A 4e/100: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Chairman of the American Delegation, China
                                Tariff Revision Commission</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Arnold</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi></placeName> [<date ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-content-and-sibling-dates" calendar="gregorian" notAfter="1921-09-09T12:45:00-04:00" notBefore="1921-09-01T00:00:00-04:00"><hi rend="italic">undated</hi></date>].<lb/>[Received September 9, 1922—12:45
                                p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>Does Department consider completed draft revised tariff as agreed by
                            Shanghai Commission must be submitted for Department’s sanction <pb facs="0939" n="819" xml:id="pg_819"/> before final publication by
                            Revision Commission? Is American delegation’s sanction to completed
                            draft sufficient for American Government ratification?</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Arnold</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>